definition.value: A protein complex that contains at least TOR (target of rapamycin) and Rictor (rapamycin-insensitive companion of TOR), or orthologs of, in complex with other signaling components. Mediates the phosphorylation and activation of PKB (also called AKT). In Saccharomyces, the complex contains Avo1p, Avo2p, Tsc11p, Lst8p, Bit61p, Slm1p, Slm2p, and Tor2p.
Heterochromatic regions of the chromosome found at the telomeres.
Heterochromatic regions of the chromosome found at silenced mating-type loci.
A two-stranded helical polymer of the protein actin.

Protease complex of the mitochondrial inner membrane whose catalytic residues lie on the intermembrane space side of the inner membrane -  involved in mitochondrial protein turnover. Contains a subunit belonging to the AAA family of ATP-dependent metalloproteases.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + a short-chain carboxylic acid + CoA -eq- AMP + diphosphate + an acyl-CoA -  short-chain fatty acids are fatty acids with a chain length of less than C6.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + a medium-chain carboxylic acid + CoA -eq- AMP + diphosphate + an acyl-CoA -  a medium-chain fatty acid is any fatty acid with a chain length of between C6 and C12.

label.value: very long-chain fatty acid-CoA ligase activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + a very-long-chain carboxylic acid + CoA -eq- AMP + diphosphate + an acyl-CoA -  a very long-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid which has a chain length greater than C22.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a cortisol receptor.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a mineralocorticoid receptor.
Combining with cortisol and transmitting the signal within the cell to trigger a change in cell activity or function.
Catalysis of the reaction -  N-beta-alanyl histamine + H2O -eq- histamine + beta-alanine.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround the nucleus and form the nuclear envelope -  excludes the intermembrane space.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround the mitochondrion and form the mitochondrial envelope.
A double membrane structure enclosing an organelle, including two lipid bilayers and the region between them. In some cases, an organelle envelope may have more than two membranes.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing in a cellular organelle, lipid bilayer of an organelle envelope.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround a chloroplast and form the chloroplast envelope.
The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of an organelle envelope.
The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of a chloroplast envelope.
The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of a chromoplast envelope.

The enclosed volume within a sealed membrane or between two sealed membranes. Encompasses the volume enclosed by the membranes of a particular organelle, e.g. endoplasmic reticulum lumen, or the space between the two lipid bilayers of a double membrane surrounding an organelle, e.g. nuclear envelope lumen.
A multilayered structure surrounding all or part of a cell -  encompasses one or more lipid bilayers, and may include a cell wall layer -  also includes the space between layers.
Any thylakoid within a plastid.
The volume enclosed by a thylakoid membrane.
The volume enclosed by a plastid thylakoid membrane.
The volume enclosed by a plasma membrane-derived thylakoid.
The volume enclosed by the nuclear inner membrane.
Any small, fluid-filled, spherical organelle enclosed by membrane or protein.
The volume enclosed by the membrane or protein that forms a vesicle.
A compartment that consists of a lumen and an enclosing membrane, and is part of an organelle.
Any of the thin, flattened membrane-bounded compartments that form the central portion of the Golgi complex.
A leucoplast in which protein is stored.
Any small, fluid-filled, spherical organelle enclosed by a lipid bilayer.

label.value: regulation of actomyosin contractile ring contraction

definition.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of contraction of the actomyosin ring involved in cytokinesis that takes place as part of a cell cycle.
The biological transducer activity that accepts energy and converts it to another form, often by transfer to another molecule within the cell.
Absorbing energy from one or more photons and transferring their energy to another molecule, usually a protein, within the cell.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with insulin-like growth factor I.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with insulin-like growth factor II.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any thioesterase enzyme.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the N-terminus of a protein that has the potential to be, or has been, modified by N-terminal myristoylation. Binding affinity is typically altered by myristoylation -  for example, N-terminal myristoylation of HIV Nef increases its affinity for calmodulin.
Catalysis of the transfer an alpha-D-glucosyl residue in a (1--gt-4)-alpha-D-glucan to the primary hydroxy group of glucose, free or combined in a (1--gt-4)-alpha-D-glucan.
A protein complex that binds interleukin-28 and interleukin-29. Composed of two subunits, IL-28R alpha and IL-10R beta.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the interleukin-28 receptor.
A membrane-bounded intracellular vesicle as initially formed upon the ingestion of particulate material by phagocytosis.

A membrane-bounded intracellular vesicle formed by maturation of an early phagosome following the ingestion of particulate material by phagocytosis -  during maturation, phagosomes acquire markers of late endosomes and lysosomes.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2-methylbutanol + NADP+ -eq- 2-methylbutanal + NADPH + H+.
A prominent mass in the cytoplasm of previtellogenic oocytes. The cloud contains both mitochondria and electron-dense granulofibrillar material (GFM) and is the source of germinal granule material.
A complex of five proteins, designated NELF-A, -B, -C, -D, and -E in human, that can physically associate with RNP polymerase II to induce transcriptional pausing.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a light chain of a myosin complex.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the head|neck region of a myosin heavy chain.
